  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering at both the federal and state levels:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n- Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n\n2. Key Federal Provisions:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 (laundering of monetary instruments)\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 (engaging in monetary transactions in property derived from specified unlawful activity)\n\n3. State Laws:\n- Many states have their own money laundering statutes that complement federal laws\n- Typically modeled after federal legislation\n- Provide additional prosecution mechanisms\n\n4. Regulatory Agencies Involved:\n- Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)\n- Internal Revenue Service (IRS)\n- Department of Justice (DOJ)\n\nThese statutes generally:\n- Criminalize financial transactions involving proceeds from illegal activities\n- Require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Establish reporting and record-keeping requirements\n- Impose significant criminal and civil penalties for violations\n\nThe laws aim to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income.",
